Waste Analysis
Authored by: Abosede Alli
Rewrite full usecase and code: Samiha Haque
Duration: 90 mins
Level: Intermediate
Pre-requisite Skills: Python, Pandas, Data Visualization

Scenario

As a city council member, I want to analyze the temporal trends and composition of waste in our city so that we can make informed decisions regarding waste management strategies and resource allocation.

As a resident, I want to understand the yearly average waste composition and trends in order to gain insights into the effectiveness of waste management efforts and identify areas for improvement.

What this use case will teach you

At the end of this use case you will:

  • Learn to load datasets using API V2.1
  • Learn to work with datetime objects and group dataframes using pandas
  • Explore different plot types such as scatter plots, bar charts, pie charts and line graphs
  • Learn to find correlation using Pearson correlation

Waste Analysis

Over the years, one of major vision of the city of Melbourne is to become a unique city, driven by innovative way of solving major problems in a more simplied way to accommodate changing needs, improve livability and maintain a leadership in sustainability. Maintaining a pool of dataset is critical to continious improvement towards a smart city goal and this is only achievable with an innovation step in our waste management awareness and processes. Currently, a number of bins are strategically located in Swanston, Bourke and Southbank streets however pedestrians attitude of dumping litters around the streets and wrong bin usage continues to cause high cost of maintenance and other losses.

The use case and exploratory data analysis provides a pathway to support the City of Melbourne in the following ways:

  • Support for the ‘Resource efficiency Usage’ which is a Priority 1.5 in Goal 1 of the vision of the city of Melbourne towards its journey in achieveing 'Future Melbourne 2026 Plan'.

  • Faciliate a sustainable environment which promote a garbage free roads, corridors and streets responsible for pollution and ecosystem management.

  • Support further discovery into the city of Melbourne becomining a leader in smart city innovation.

Datasets used:

  • waste-collected-per-month

This dataset mainly contains the date(year-month) and the different categories of waste which include residential waste, public litter bins, dumped rubbish, street_sweepings waste, mattresses, commingled recycling, cardboard recycling, hardwaste to landfill waste,hardwaste recovered waste, hardwaste total and green waste throughout the city of Melbourne. This dataset is imported from Melbourne Open Data website, using API V2.1.

In [238]:
base_url='https://data.melbourne.vic.gov.au/api/explore/v2.1/catalog/datasets/'
dataset_id='waste-collected-per-month'


url=f'{base_url}{dataset_id}/exports/csv'
params={'select':'*','limit':-1,'lang':'en','timezone':'UTC'}

response=requests.get(url,params=params)

if response.status_code==200:
    url_content=response.content.decode('utf-8')
    waste_df=pd.read_csv(StringIO(url_content),delimiter=';')
    print(waste_df.head(10))
else:
    print(f'Request failed with status code {response.status_code}')

Temporal analysis of wastes (2010-2019)¶

Street sweepings It can be seen that street sweeping wastes follow a similar trend throughout all years from 2010 to 2019 with large amount of street sweeping waste produced in August. However, the amount throughout the years has substantially decreased to approximately half. It can also be seen that in 2010 July, there was a large street sweeping waste collected which could either be an anomaly or due to natural/societal causes.

Residential waste It can be seen that residential wastes follow a similar trend throughout all years from 2010 to 2019 and is on an increasing trend. 2019 had the highest residential waste which mostly likely was due to COVID.

Annual waste analysis¶

I calculated the sum of all the different types of wastes in each year and plotted a bar chart. I excluded 2009 and 2019 since both had missing months. It can be seen that the sum of wastes increased overtime which is natural but the increase is not drastic. From 2010 to 2019 the sum of wastes increased by a little over 10000.

Yearly average waste composition (2010, 2015, 2019)¶

The three piecharts below represent the yearly mean waste in 2010, 2015 and 2019. Residential waste covers majority of the percentage and has increased over the years. Cardboard waste, street sweepings and dumped rubbish has decreased significantly over the years.

In [251]:
cols = ['residential','public_litter_bins','dumped_rubbish','street_sweepings',	'mattresses','commingled_recycling','cardboard']
fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(20, 5))
for i, year in enumerate(['2010', '2015', '2019']):
    ax = axs[i]
    ax.set_title(f'Average waste pie chart for {year}')
    year_data = yearly_df_avg[yearly_df_avg['year']==year]
    
    sizes = year_data[cols].values[0]
    ax.pie(sizes, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=90)
    ax.axis('equal') 
    ax.legend(cols, loc="center left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0, 0.5, 1))
    
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Correlation analysis between residential waste vs public litter bins and residential waste vs street sweepings¶

It can be seen that the yearly average of residential waste and public litter bins have a highe negative correlated of 76% which can also be seen from the scatter plot. The increase in residential waste is likely to cause the decrease in public litter bin waste since people are likely using garbage bins at home instead.

Comparison of Recycling and Waste Recovery Trends Over Time¶

The plot below displays the comingled recycling and cardboard recyling trend over the years. Comingled recycling has increased over the years with a sharp increase in 2018. Whereas cardboard recycling has stayed constant over the years till 2018 after which it started to decrease a little. It can also be seen that the amount of comingled recycling waste is much higher than cardboard recycling waste in all the years.

The plot below displays the hardwaste recovered and hardwaste to landfill trend over the years. It can be seen that the amount of hardwaste sent to landfill has been increasing over the years with the highest amount recorded in 2020. Hardwaste recovery has started from 2015 onwards and is slowly increasing. But the amount of hardwaste sent to landfill is still almost thrice as much as hardwaste recovered. However, in 2016 hardwaste sent to landfill was mostly recovered since there is a sharp drop in the hardwaste to landfill plot and a sharp increase in the hardwaste recovered plot.

Findings¶

  • Street Sweepings: There was a noticeable decrease in street sweeping waste over the years, with a peak in August and a significant reduction in 2010 July.
  • Residential Waste: Residential waste showed an increasing trend over the years, peaking in 2019, likely due to the impact of COVID-19.
  • Hardwaste to Landfill: Hardwaste sent to landfill exhibited a sharp increase in September each year.
  • Hardwaste Recovered: Hardwaste recovery began in 2015, with varying amounts recovered in different months in subsequent years.
  • The total sum of wastes increased over time, with residential waste being the highest contributor.
  • Residential waste covers majority of the percentage of wastes and has increased over the years. Cardboard waste, street sweepings and dumped rubbish has decreased significantly over the years.
  • Scatter plots and correlation coefficients revealed relationships between residential waste and public litter bins, as well as between residential waste and street sweepings. As residential waste increases, public litter binds and street sweepings decrease.
  • Comingled recycling has increased over the years compared to cardboard recycling.
  • There is not enough hardwaste recovered compared to hardwaste sent to landfills.
